STAC32 Final Project: Racial Disparity in Wealth Distribution in the USA

Agam Chavan, Felix Cheung, Stephanie Wong, Akaash Palaparthy, Kritika Pandey



Abstract

This project aims to throw light on the disparity experienced by racial and minority groups in the USA with respect to wealth distribution and student loans. While everyone is aware of the racial inequalities present in the USA, this project quantifies the same with data sourced from Urban Institute and the US Census, via tidytuesday. The datasets used in our analysis include information on race, income level and student debt. Through statistical analysis, we realised that the average family wealth (normalized to 2016) for White families is significantly higher than that for Black or Hispanic families in the US. This disparity has existed since several years. There is a high correlation between race and average income (P < 0.05) and the largest wealth disparity exists between White and Black races in the US. To provide historical context, we also consider the Civil Rights Movement and any impact it might have had on social indicators. Disproportionate wealth distribution influences one’s need for student loans. Students from the Black community had a higher percentage of debt, compared to their White and Hispanic colleagues.

Introduction

This project focuses on the wealth gap created as a result of systemic/institutional racism. We look at historical data and the impact of the Civil Rights Movement on curbing the gap. Racial inequality is defined as “imbalances in the distribution of power, economic resources and opportunities” (Shapiro, 2004). Such social injustices have been present in American society since several years, with several monumental efforts taken to right this wrong, most notably the Civil Rights Movement (1954-1968). This ended legalized racial discrimination, disenfranchisement and racial segregation in the US. Unfortunately, these reforms have not been able to completely curb institutional racism in the US. It is a form of racism “that is embedded in the laws and regulations of a society”, and “manifests as discrimination in areas such as criminal justice, employment, housing, healthcare, education and political representation” (Shapiro, 2004). This project focuses on the disproportionate disadvantages faced by minority communities in the US, especially in income levels, family wealth and the burden of student loans. We have decided to focus on income, wealth and student debt since access to money and education largely determine an individual’s quality of life and standing in society. Most of our findings are in line with what one might expect, given the social atmosphere in the US. However, being able to support known facts with quantified evidence and data is always a benefit and provides new perspectives.

The relationship between race and income_mean:

We would be running an analysis of variance (Welch ANOVA) below. \(Ho\): All race groups have same income mean. \(Ha\): Not all income means the same, at least one race group is different from others.

oneway.test(income_mean~race,data=households)

    One-way analysis of means (not assuming equal variances)

data:  income_mean and race
F = 1912.4, num df = 3.00, denom df = 715.24, p-value < 2.2e-16

Observation 1: There is a high correlation between income mean and the races, p-value is very small. As the p-value < 0.05, there is signifance difference within the race groups. Therefore, we can reject the null that income means are equal. As there is more than 3 groups, we would do a Games-Howell test to see where these differences lie.

gamesHowellTest(income_mean~factor(race),data=households)

Observation 2: The p-value is even smaller than before so there is still a correlation between race and income. As p-value < 0.05, which means that at least one group has a different median than other race groups. Mood’s median test is really similar to the F-test in ANOVA: it’s testing the null hypothesis that the race groups all have the same median (of income_median), against the alternative that the null is not true. We rejected this null, but we don’t know which race group differ significantly from which. To resolve this, we do all the pairwise Mood’s median tests on all pairs of groups, and we would look at the adjusted P-values to see how the race group differ in terms of income median.

pairwise_median_test(households,income_median,race)

Observation: By comparing income_median of each race group to another, they all have significant differences because their adjusted P-value < 0.05
